AB  - Many people like city life in its variety, that is characteristic in its availability of cultural activities and social tolerance that manifests itself in coexistence of different life-styles. The city has to be lively and multifaceted both during the day and at night; therefore it is good that the center of the city is populated. The city must ensure opportunities for citizens' meetings; it has to be appropriate for everyday activities, festivities, culture events and any other functions.
   Historic urban environment is an interesting challenge for these functions in conjunction with the historic buildings ecosystems. The most important challenge for ensuring these functions are considerations dealing with microclimate of historic urban environment.
   The historic urban environment as an eco-system is a single whole, in which plants, animals, micro-organisms and people interact, creating a special microclimate. Climate control continued assurance is one of the major tasks and major challenges of urban planning professionals, particularly in the urban environment is creating new construction volumes with modern materials, which give rise to the old town ecosystem irreversible destruction, disrupting the natural microclimate. Historic buildings deteriorate, comfort requirements of inhabitants of these buildings are increasing, and therefore careful and neutral solutions for microclimate are needed for restoring and improving energy efficiency of these buildings.
   This research is needed to consider how to evaluate which materials and ways should be used for reconstruction and insulation of historic buildings, what are the main risk factors and criteria for the selection of suitable ecologic building materials to conserve historic urban ecosystem.
