AB  - The legacy of the Norwegian landscape architect Knut Ove Hillestad (1963-1991) The Norwegian landscape architect Knut Ove Hillestad was employed at the Norwegian Watershed and Energy Directorate INVE) in the years 1963 until 1991, when he reshaped watershed landscapes affected by large-scale hydropower developments The taproot of this work was his concept of leaving living nature, by which he meant that nature ought to be regenerated and left diverse and self-reproductive The concept may be regarded as a third way of protecting nature, between the classical regimes of preservative growth and "ecological ideologies" The intellectual roots of living nature may be found in two distinct phases of Hiflestad's carrier In the 1960s, NVE's nature management was inspired by the Swedish organisation Samfundet for Hembygdsvard This organisation was primarily oriented toward cultural and aesthetic issues, it was friendly towards industrial growth, and the landscape architects were its most influential expertise In this period, Hillestad was a dedicated representative of his profession In the 1970s, he became more a manager to a network dominated by natural scientists, mostly biologists This was a growing profession with significant objections to manipulating nature These groups, however, lay new premises to Hillestad's activity, but also acquired the landscape architect's perception of landscape care as an act not of conserving, but of creation
