AB  - There are various sources available for examination of Icelandic attitudes to Norway and Norwegians from 1814 to the Second World War. Although the attitudes of Icelanders were not identical in every way, generalizations can be made. After the dissolution of the union between Denmark and Norway in 1814, Iceland and Norway did not belong to the same state, but in the course of time connections between the two countries increased in various fields. The close historical ties between the two countries and a common cultural heritage, Iceland having been largely settled from Norway and later becoming part of the Norwegian state, had a bearing on the attitudes of many Icelanders towards the country and its inhabitants. To some Icelanders, a journey to Norway was something like a pilgrimage. Icelanders were impressed with the Norwegian landscape and thought positively about the nation. They took much interest in contemporary Norwegian culture and greatly enjoyed the literature of the country. Many Icelanders had a positive attitude to the New Norwegian language. Some popular movements in Norway had considerable influence in Iceland; for example, the Norwegian Youth Societies Movement, den frilynte ungdomsrorsla, was a model for the influential Icelandic Youth Societies Movement. In some ways, Norway was seen as a model by many Icelanders as regards political and economic development. In their struggle for increased self-government within the Danish state, many Icelanders were encouraged by what they saw as progress in Norway, the country being in practice nearly independent within the union with Sweden until achieving statehood in 1905. Icelanders also looked to Norway as an example of progress in farming and fishing. Examined in the context of the Icelanders' attitudes to other countries, their feelings towards Norway and Norwegians were particularly positive.
