AB  - In regulated rivers, reduced habitat size due to reduced flows is often considered as a bottleneck for fish production. Increasing the flow will lead to a loss in hydropower production, and in high-head hydropower schemes this is costly. Finding a balance between hydropower production and environmental interests are thus vital. Residual flow targets are usually determined after analyzing modeled or measured discharge to wetted area relationships or by using natural low flow metrics like Q(95) (5-percentile of yearly discharge). Effects of habitat quality is usually ignored or underestimated, wetted area is used as a proxy for the biological productivity of a river [7, 8]. Often and sometimes alternatively, to residual flows, groundsills and other small impoundments have been designed to maximize wetted area in residual flow stretches [7, 8]. The underlying assumption is that an increase in wetted area corresponds to a linear increase in the fish productivity of the river. Our results suggest that this assumption is not necessarily correct. Improved physical habitat quality, determined as a function of spawning and shelter availability, can compensate for losses in wetted area and even multiply total fish production. Instead of using just wetted area as a proxy for fish production, both habitat size (wetted area) AND physical habitat quality ought to be addressed.
